\f1\i0 ) (988\'961069) was born in either Chativavo ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chittagong"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Chittagong}}), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengal"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Bengal}} or Jagora, Bengal in India.  Tilopa's name translates to "the tahini maker". He lived along the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganges_River"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Ganges River}}, with wild ladies as a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tantra"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 tantric practitioner}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahasiddha"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mahasiddha}}.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tilopa#cite_note-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [1]}} He practiced {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anuttarayoga_Tantra"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Anuttarayoga Tantra}}, a set of spiritual practices intended to accelerate the process of attaining {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhahood"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Buddhahood}}. He became a holder of all the tantric lineages, possibly the only person in his day to do so. As well as the way of Insight, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahamudra"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Mahamudra}} he learned and passed on the Way of Methods, today known as the 6 Yogas of Naropa, and guru yoga.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tilopa#cite_note-Nydahl_2019_119-2"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [2]}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naropa"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Naropa}} is considered his main student. At {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pashupatinath_Temple"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Pashupatinath temple}} premise, greatest {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Hindu}} shrine of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepal"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Nepal}}, there are two caves where Tilopa attained {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siddhi"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Siddhi}} and initiated his disciple Naropa. \
